segments.text: See, there was concern that the Japanese might be able to start some diseases against livestock which were highly contagious and easily transmitted diseases that could spread across the country and be very damaging to U.S. and Canadian food supply.
That was one of the main reasons for our program on Rinderpest in Canada at War Disease Control Station.
During that period of time in 42 and 43, the Japanese launched literally hundreds of hot air balloons in Japan, which because of prevailing
air currents at about 60,000 feet were able to fly over to the United States and Canada on their own.
In very large numbers they came.

And we were all concerned that they might load these with contagious disease materials which when they landed here in the United States and Canada would be picked up by livestock and spread all over the country.
But fortunately
the security was so good that the Japanese never learned that their balloons were getting here, that they were launching in Japan during that time period.

So though there were lots of them came, and we had US and Canadian aircraft out beating these balloons down, and then men picking up material from them and bringing them to our lab, which we tested in cattle and livestock.
We never picked up a hot disease from any of that material.
What did they send?
Well, they sent a few of these hand grenades and bombs over, which would explode when they were touched by people.
And there were just a few people killed with these.
But for the most part, they continued to send them because they used them as a propaganda
tool for their munitions plants in Japan.
They'd have a big gathering and launch a lot of these balloons and tell their workers that they were sending these over there to wipe out the Canadians and the US citizens, and launch a lot of them.
But they didn't know they were getting here, but they were.
They were coming.
It's surprising that they didn't send any disease, because they were working on these things.
That's right, they were.
And they could have sent them, but
Not thinking they were getting here, they didn't load them, except with a few little bombs and things.
I was wondering about another thing, too.
And that is, I forgot to ask you about this when we were talking earlier about it.
We were talking about the relationships with government.
I was wondering about the relationship that you and the Institute had with the Colombian government.
How did that work?
Well, it worked very well.
And we had actually very little to do with it, because that had been well established by the Rockefeller Foundation.
They had a very good liaison with the Colombian government.
And many of the higher Colombian officials had received graduate training in the United States with scholarships provided by the Rockefeller Foundation.
So they were in an excellent standing with Rockefeller and accepted us as part of that overall team.
So we had no problems there.
Did a lot of the technicians and the researchers, did a lot of them know Spanish?
Yes, that's right.
So there was a good communication between the UN and the Colombian veterinarians.
And we usually had some Colombian veterinarians and technicians working with us down there.
So it was a joint effort.
How were the facilities?
They were excellent.
They were provided really by the Rockefeller Foundation.
They furnished us with excellent labs both in Bogota and down in Cali.

And it was a good arrangement, really, because we would typically have a Colombian veterinarian who was our field man that would make contacts with livestock producers and people with whom we would work in the field.
For example, they would make the arrangements for us to go out and vaccinate a year's crop of calves for a vaccination trial.

and work it all out, and we'd go do the work and follow through with them, and the farmer would benefit, and the local government would benefit from it, and everybody would be happy, and we weren't so directly involved with local people, you see, because of that, which made it easy for us.
Sure, you didn't have to set things up.
And how did the people, the farmers or the peasants, how did they respond to you?
Well, there was never any problem.
We got along very well.
They were probably very happy to see you coming.
Did you ever do any work with the Peace Corps?
No.
No, I never did.
Because the Peace Corps must have, I'm sure they were in Columbia at that time.
Yes, they were.
And they must have been doing some similar type work, vaccinations, building things.
Most of their efforts were with people rather than with livestock, so we didn't have.
You know, we knew about their presence and would meet them from time to time, but we didn't have much to do with it.
Why'd you retire?
Well, because I became 67 years old, and the university retired everybody at that time when they were 65 or thereabouts, you see, and I stayed on two more years.
Now I think they'll let you stay on to age 70, but they didn't at that time.
Yeah, I would have been happy to stay on for quite a few more years because I have good health and good shape.
No reason not to.
In fact, I've been busier in many ways since I left out there than I was before.
Which brings me to another question.
What have you been doing since retirement?
Well, my son and I started an insulation business here in town in 1977.
And we're still going strong with that.
What's the name of it?
Insulate.
Oh, really?
That's your company?
Yeah, that's my company.
And my son is over there.
Does he run it, then, on the day-to-day business?
Yeah, and I spend a lot of time over there, too.
I still do.
I kept the books for the first two and a half years, using a little of my accounting training from Idaho.
And in the meantime, I've bought 15 rent houses here in town.
No kidding.
And I maintain those myself, and my wife and I do.
between the rent houses and the insulation business and a little bit of occasional consulting work, plus a book of poems and making chimes and some land out in the country to play with.
I don't like for things to do.
And I've been director of the Bank of A&M since 1967.
Serve on some committees up there.
Before that, from about 67 to 80, I was a third owner of the ornamental castings company out here that makes ornamental things.
My son was out there until he shifted over to these other things.
Now, why'd you shift to Enslade?
Well, Al got tired of working in that job and wanted to do something more on his own.
So he left out there and I sold my
most of my stock from ornamental casting.
He started his insulation business.
It was really the first one in town that had the first energy store in town where we sold stoves and solar screens and a lot of things along with the insulation work.
Now it's become more competitive.
There are about a half a dozen operations in town now.
How's business been?
Well, it's slacked off a bit for that reason, and so now Al is interested in selling it and doing something else to get out of it.
He'd like to get in some other thing.
But we've never lacked for things to do.
Now, is there something else that I've missed that we should talk about as far as the Institute is concerned?
I don't really think so.
I don't know best how to handle this problem of its current status out there.
I don't want to be unfair to anybody.
I don't like to downgrade somebody just because I don't agree with what they've done.
I just hope that that administrative level can be squared away and made to realize that there's an opportunity there that we should all take advantage of.
So, I'll need to edit that part of this thing pretty carefully.
Well, thank you very much for this interview and we'll come out and we'll get...
